In the article in the Sung Shu, Je takes the surname "Wa" (倭) as did the previous Japanese king Jin, but does not clarify his relationship to Jin. Since they do not name the continuation, there is a theory that Je and Chin were not close blood relatives, and since the [[Nihon Shoki]] shows a struggle in the succession to the throne after [[:en:Emperor Nintoku|Emperor Nintoku]], the possibility of the existence of such a struggle over the throne is pointed out {{Sfn|河内春人|2018|pp=73-119}} In addition, since the {{ill|Wazui|ja|倭隋|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Wazui|qq=}} can be seen as a particularly powerful royal family in the Chin period, there is a theory that there were two royal forces at that time ([[Mozu Tombs|Mozu Kofun Cluster]] and [[Furuichi Kofun Cluster]]), and that Je may have been a lineage of this Wazui {{Sfn|河内春人|2018|pp=73-119}}。

=== Comparison of the tombs ===
During the period of activity of the [[Five kings of Wa]], the tombs of the great kings were constructed in the [[Mozu Tombs]] and [[Furuichi Kofun Cluster]] ([[Osaka Prefecture]], [[Sakai|Sakai City]], [[:en:Habikino|Habikino City]], [[:en:Fujiidera|Fujiidera]]), and Je's tomb is assumed to be one of them.<ref>[http://www.mozu-furuichi.jp/jp/story/ "Wa" no Monogatari] (Headquarters Committee for the Promotion of the Mozu and Furuichi Kofun Group World Cultural Heritage Registration, "Mozu and Furuichi Kofun Group")</ref> These tombs are now designated as mausoleums by the [[:en:Imperial Household Agency|Miyouchi Agency]], so there is a lack of archaeological data to date them, but one theory compares them to the [[:en:Ichinoyama Kofun|Ichinoyama Kofun]] (the current imperial tomb of [[:en:Emperor Ingyo|Emperor Ingyo]]).

Another archaeological source is the {{ill|Inaridai Sword|lt="Gift of Wang"|ja|鉄剣・鉄刀銘文|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Inaridai Sword|qq=}} excavated from the {{ill|Inaridai Kofun Group|ja|稲荷台1号墳|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Inaridai Kofun Group|qq=|comment=enwiki is a redirect}} (Ichihara City, Chiba Prefecture). (or Chin), since he is self-explanatory only by writing "Wang".{{Sfn|Mori Kosho|2010|pp=51-55}}{{Sfn|Kouchi Haruhito|2018|pp=73-119}} It should be noted, however, that the [[Inariyama Sword|iron sword from Inariyama Kofun]] inscription and the {{ill|Eta Funayama Sword|lt=iron sword from Etafuneyama Kofun|ja|鉄剣・鉄刀銘文|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Eta Funayama Sword|qq=}} inscription are distinct from the "Great King" of the [[Inariyama Sword]]{{Sfn|河内春人|2018|pp=73-119}}。

